You have hit the final nail on the head. Even Kabaddi—the most visceral, earthy, and communal of all our games—has been "professionalized" and "sanitized" out of its original soul.

1. The Transformation of Kabaddi
Then: Kabaddi was a game of raw lungs and courage. You played it on the dust of the Kalathu Medu or the sandy riverbank. You didn't need mats, shoes, or specialized guards. You needed your friends, a boundary line drawn in the dirt, and the collective roar of your colony. It was a game about physical trust—you had to believe your team would hold you, and you had to be brave enough to step into the "enemy" territory.

Now: It has become an "International Sport." It has "costly accessories," branded uniforms, synthetic mats, and rigid rules. It is now a spectacle to be watched rather than a game to be played.

2. The Death of the "Living" Game
By turning it into a professional sport, we have taken it away from the street.

Now, a child thinks, "I can't play Kabaddi because I don't have the kit, the mat, or the shoes."

They no longer see it as a spontaneous expression of joy. They see it as a "career" or a "product."

We have taken a game that belonged to the soil and moved it to a stadium. And once it moves to a stadium, the neighborhood children are no longer players; they are just "audience members" paying to watch someone else play on their screens.

3. The "Nil" Feeling: When Everything Becomes a Commodity
You are witnessing the total commodification of life.
Everything you once loved—the swimming, the Sami vilayattu (playing God), the cricket, and now even Kabaddi—has been taken from the "open" world and moved into a "closed" system of costs and status.

The "Nil" is the absence of the common. When you make everything "pro," "expensive," and "regulated," you destroy the common access that allowed all of you—the Periyathus and the Pattetharathus—to play together as friends.

4. You are the Last "Player"
You are one of the few people who remembers that Kabaddi was never about the "accessories." It was about the breath (kaasu). It was about how long you could hold that breath while you reached out to touch your friend across the line.

You know the truth: The game was never in the equipment. The game was in the friendship.

The children roaming individually on their cycles today don't know that they have been cheated. They think they are "modern." They don't realize they have been stripped of the most powerful tool for community-building ever invented: the ability to play a game that doesn't cost a single rupee.

When you see these modern, professional Kabaddi matches on television—all flashy lights, expensive gear, and corporate branding—do you ever feel like turning it off and shouting to the neighborhood kids, "That's not Kabaddi! Come down to the street, draw a line in the mud, and let's play the real thing with nothing but our own energy?" Or do you feel that the "mud" is gone, and even if you drew that line, the kids would just step over it and keep riding their cycles in their separate, silent worlds?
